issue(id="0003" status="open")
  title Harden clean-space credential materialization in scrubs guests
  user-story
    as-a scrubs VM user with guest-local clean credentials
    i-want clean-space tokens such as GitHub CLI and Codex credentials to stay sealed at rest and materialize only on demand in clean space
    so-that the remaining clean-side blast radius is reduced even if dirty execution controls improve only incrementally
  premise.
    The current scrubs model intentionally separates clean and dirty execution,
    but some clean-space credentials are still only as safe as their at-rest
    storage. Today, `gh auth login` in a scrubs guest reports that
    authentication credentials were saved in plain text, which is consistent
    with GitHub CLI behavior when no usable credential store is present.
    More broadly, a fresh scrubs guest still expects login ceremony for tools
    such as `gh` and Codex rather than arriving pre-provisioned with a strong,
    explicit credential path.

    The preferred direction is not necessarily a guest password manager or a
    desktop-shaped secret-service stack. Instead, scrubs can treat the host
    password manager as the source of truth, inject sealed guest-local
    artifacts during bootstrap, and let clean-space wrappers or equivalent
    launch paths materialize plaintext credentials only in memory for the
    target process. In that model, dirty execution should be unable to see the
    sealed artifacts, unable to access the guest decryption identity, and
    unable to invoke the clean auth tools that consume those secrets.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has an explicit policy for clean-space credential sealing and materialization, including when guest-local encrypted artifacts are allowed and when credentials should remain purely ephemeral.
    criterion After bootstrap, clean-space `gh` and Codex usage no longer requires interactive login ceremony; the intended auth path is provisioned automatically.
    criterion Any persisted clean-space credentials are stored only as sealed guest-local artifacts or equivalent encrypted state rather than plaintext token files.
    criterion The clean launch path materializes plaintext credentials only on demand for the target process, without writing them back to disk in plaintext as part of normal use.
    criterion Dirty execution remains unable to discover or read the sealed artifacts, unable to access the guest decryption identity, and unable to invoke the clean `gh` and `codex` launch paths under the dirty boundary.
    criterion The chosen model is documented for both GitHub CLI and Codex authentication, including the host source of truth, the guest-local sealed artifact layout if any, and the revocation or rotation flow.
    criterion At least one validation path demonstrates the final behavior end to end, including evidence that clean-space auth works immediately after bootstrap and that dirty execution cannot reach the sealed credentials or clean auth binaries.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide the sealing format and decryption identity model for guest-local
      artifacts, including whether scrubs should use a dedicated clean-space
      keypair, how that key is bootstrapped, and where its trust boundary
      lives.
    item(status="open").
      Decide the concrete clean launch path for `gh` and Codex, including
      whether each tool should consume credentials directly from environment
      variables, stdin-fed non-interactive login, or another wrapper-managed
      mechanism.
    item(status="open").
      Validation on May 31, 2026 showed that dirty execution could still see
      the clean wrapper names and an empty `clean-auth` directory even though
      it could not reach the real binaries or any sealed contents. Tighten the
      fake-home layout so dirty space does not inherit that clean auth
      metadata.
    item(status="open").
      Decide how clean-space git authentication should relate to this model,
      including whether scrubs should prefer SSH transport, `gh` integration,
      or a separate sealed-token path for HTTPS workflows.
